\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Integrals of the Form 
\begin_inset Formula $\int\cos^{n}(x)dx.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

In this note, we are interested in integrals of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{n}:=\int\cos^{n}(x)dx$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Case 1
\series default
: Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $n=2k+1$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\mathbb{Z}_{\geq0}$
\end_inset

.
 In this case, we simply do a 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 substitution with 
\begin_inset Formula $u=\sin(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{n}$
\end_inset

 becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
I_{n} & =\int\cos^{2k}(x)du\\
 & =\int\left(1-\sin^{2}(x)\right)^{k}du\\
 & =\int\left(1-u^{2}\right)^{k}du,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which is easy to solve.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Case 2
\series default
: Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $n=2k$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 In this case, we do integration by parts with 
\begin_inset Formula $u=\cos^{n-1}(x)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $dv=\cos(x)dx$
\end_inset

.
 Then one derives a recursive formula:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
I_{n}=\cos^{n-1}(x)\sin(x)+(n-1)I_{n-1}+(n-1)I_{n+1},
\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{n-1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{n+1}$
\end_inset

 fall under Case 1, so we are done.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Case 3
\series default
: Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $n=-2k-1$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\mathbb{Z}_{\geq0}$
\end_inset

.
 In this case, we do integration by parts with 
\begin_inset Formula $u=\sec^{n-2}(x)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $dv=\sec^{2}(x)dx$
\end_inset

.
 Then one derives a recursive formula:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(n-1)I_{n}=\sec^{n-2}(x)\tan(x)+(n-2)I_{n-2},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_body
